00:46:16,460 --> 00:46:21,440
J.J. Abrams helped us with some stuff. I helped them. He's helped them.

451
00:46:21,460 --> 00:46:29,960
You know, it's so hard to make these movies that most people if they get a phone call and you're like, I need help,

452
00:46:29,960 --> 00:46:33,380
people will drop whatever they're doing. There you are on screen again, by the way.

453
00:46:33,380 --> 00:46:36,720
Briefly on screen. Well, I was briefly on screen.

454
00:46:48,840 --> 00:46:53,225
That damn thing changed colors like 30 times over the course of production.

455
00:46:53,225 --> 00:46:55,680
Let's figure out what it should look like.

456
00:46:55,680 --> 00:46:59,240
What noise it should make.

457
00:46:59,240 --> 00:47:06,000
I love how conversational these guys are in all the scenes. Not just them, but him and Gwyneth.

458
00:47:06,900 --> 00:47:08,400
Rhodey.

459
00:47:10,120 --> 00:47:16,300
We really tried to hold it to the standard of if it were just like an independent comedy or something.

460
00:47:50,490 --> 00:47:57,070
All these scenes were two cameras. One on Robert, one on Jeff. One on Robert, one on Gwyneth.

461
00:47:57,070 --> 00:48:00,550
One on Robert, one on Terrence.

462
00:48:01,390 --> 00:48:05,450
Because we would change it. We'd mix it up all the time. I always wanted to make sure I could

463
00:48:05,450 --> 00:48:08,870
use anything good that came.

464
00:48:09,510 --> 00:48:15,890
Sometimes composition and lighting was sacrificed. There's not a lot of intricate camera moves in this film.

465
00:48:16,210 --> 00:48:20,490
I prefer to capture something real happening.

466
00:48:28,590 --> 00:48:33,488
So Jeff loved to have a script a good three months before he did the scene.

467
00:48:33,488 --> 00:48:35,970
He would write more notes than I would

468
00:48:35,970 --> 00:48:38,482
have as a director on the opposite page.

469
00:48:38,482 --> 00:48:43,570
Robert would come in and bounce the script off the wall of the trailer every day.

470
00:48:44,670 --> 00:48:47,230
This was a good call.

471
00:48:49,570 --> 00:48:52,530
Nobody thought to put this guy in a movie.

472
00:48:54,330 --> 00:48:56,810
Let's give it a shot.

473
00:48:56,810 --> 00:48:59,090
I like the tone of it.

474
00:49:02,610 --> 00:49:07,210
Her leg was broken in this scene too. She broke her leg over the course of the film.

475
00:49:07,210 --> 00:49:15,790
Not on the film. We found out that she needed surgery. Being the trooper that she was, she...

476
00:49:15,790 --> 00:49:20,070
This is the heart of the movie. This was Jon's idea.

477
00:49:22,370 --> 00:49:30,950
I was sitting in a chair with a prosthesis and fake legs for 12 hours. At the end of the day, that's probably

478
00:49:30,950 --> 00:49:34,490
my favorite scene. Let's just let it play.

479
00:51:03,160 --> 00:51:08,520
You get it? Operation the little, uh... There we go.

480
00:51:08,520 --> 00:51:10,020
Okay.

481
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:22,000
That was improvised.

482
00:51:26,560 --> 00:51:31,620
What I like about how she does comedy is she's not- she doesn't do comedy,

483
00:51:31,620 --> 00:51:34,420
so she just plays it dead real.

484
00:51:34,420 --> 00:51:38,540
It's cool, the way- I like how people play comedy.

485
00:51:39,040 --> 00:51:43,920
So when they're building all these props and things, they're like, so how deep do you want the thing?

486
00:51:43,920 --> 00:51:46,940
I figure realistically it's going to be about 2 inches. We're like, no, she should be able to

487
00:51:46,940 --> 00:51:51,880
get her whole wrist in there. But that's not real. I said, let me just do it.

488
00:51:52,320 --> 00:51:54,657
If they're laughing, they won't mind.

489
00:51:54,657 --> 00:51:59,900
There's someone standing two feet away from us the whole time with a huge bag of sludge.

490
00:51:59,900 --> 00:52:03,931
They're like, "can I just reset the inorganic plasmic discharge?

491
00:52:03,931 --> 00:52:06,000
And this is what sells the whole thing,

492
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:11,260
right? So there was a big rubber body for all that, and then on the cut, he

493
00:52:11,260 --> 00:52:13,620
hops out.

494
00:52:14,560 --> 00:52:19,960
This is one of the scenes where Robert's trainer had notes on lighting. He's like, can we just get the top

495
00:52:19,960 --> 00:52:25,660
light? He goes, alright, okay, this is terrible. This is good lighting.

496
00:52:25,660 --> 00:52:33,040
For you right here, top light. You look like Rocky II, man, where you all cut up and shredded.

497
00:52:33,800 --> 00:52:37,300
"You more shredded than a julienne salad, man"

498
00:52:38,140 --> 00:52:40,980
How funny is he in Tropic Thunder? Forget it.

499
00:52:44,520 --> 00:52:51,020
He sent me a picture of him in the makeup from Tropic Thunder. I was like, you're kidding, right?

500
00:52:51,420 --> 00:52:57,880
That's going to be breaking about the time we're coming out, and they're going to be boycotting our movie.

501
00:52:57,900 --> 00:53:03,840
He says, maybe, but I think it's going to work out. Sure enough, there was no backlash.

502
00:53:06,340 --> 00:53:09,700
The R-word [retard] that was in the story.

503
00:53:19,720 --> 00:53:21,860
It might be the first time in Marvel

504
00:53:21,860 --> 00:53:27,720
history that we allude to the fact that one of the lead characters may have had an evening with a tranny.

505
00:53:28,740 --> 00:53:31,560
Because that was also improvised.

506
00:54:12,230 --> 00:54:15,930
So this next little bit of business here,

507
00:54:16,270 --> 00:54:19,930
and working on the suit, he just...

508
00:54:20,210 --> 00:54:24,830
This is all... We're late in the game...

509
00:54:27,770 --> 00:54:31,483
This whole interface where he interacts with the hologram was something we were just...

510
00:54:31,483 --> 00:54:33,190
I was like, Robert, just move your hands

511
00:54:33,190 --> 00:54:37,170
around. I'll put something in around you.

512
00:54:37,610 --> 00:54:40,070
But just move the thing.

513
00:54:40,750 --> 00:54:46,210
And we got contacted by the military saying, How did you know about this technology?

514
00:54:48,110 --> 00:54:52,000
And they actually asked us for permission to use this stuff

515
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:57,210
as a demonstration of what their stuff does, because they can't do it yet.

516
00:54:57,950 --> 00:55:01,410
This is a 60 mile an hour windstorm.

517
00:55:01,410 --> 00:55:03,910
They were going to call it a weather day. I said, No, no, no.

518
00:55:03,910 --> 00:55:08,030
Hand out goggles. This was even windier the day you were shooting.

519
00:55:08,650 --> 00:55:12,910
And it has... It gives it that weird... Something feels like Star Wars about this.

520
00:55:12,910 --> 00:55:15,410
I kind of get it.

521
00:55:20,170 --> 00:55:25,150
If anybody wants to know what happens when three boulders fall on your head, that's what it looks like.

522
00:55:26,790 --> 00:55:32,170
We did the research. This is a great piece of...

523
00:55:33,530 --> 00:55:37,370
Just the negative space on the mask and him wearing the goggles. I thought it was really cool.

524
00:55:37,370 --> 00:55:44,450
Those goggles I pulled off of our assistant visual effects supervisor. He ordered them from China.

525
00:55:44,450 --> 00:55:47,730
Army surplus goggles. I said, Those. Give him a hand.

526
00:55:47,730 --> 00:55:55,550
By the way, these were going to be several hundred thousand scenes where I'm just doing the Tony Stark tweaks with his machines and

527
00:55:55,550 --> 00:55:58,270
all that. See that in the background? The gantry on the ceiling?

528
00:55:58,270 --> 00:56:03,170
That's digital. And that was a big argument with the studio, because if you didn't show that there,

529
00:56:03,170 --> 00:56:06,230
you couldn't have him being suited up later.

530
00:56:06,930 --> 00:56:11,630
That's there for you guys. So you can enjoy the movie.

531
00:56:11,630 --> 00:56:18,330
That wasn't there. These are the two dumbest robots in history. They didn't do anything.

532
00:56:18,330 --> 00:56:21,390
Therefore, I made them my friends.

533
00:56:23,930 --> 00:56:29,210
So this is the first time I was ever involved with visual effects to this scale. And I always thought about...

534
00:56:29,210 --> 00:56:32,730
Nobody ever uses it for humor.

535
00:56:33,190 --> 00:56:38,810
And it's very hard to get the timing just right on this stuff, because it takes so many months.

536
00:56:38,810 --> 00:56:42,110
Everybody's expecting something heroic here.

537
00:56:53,970 --> 00:56:59,670
Is there someone standing around with a fire extinguisher? Jon goes, get him over here. What was the guy's name?

538
00:56:59,670 --> 00:57:05,130
Jeter? The SFX guy? Günther.

539
00:57:05,130 --> 00:57:08,550
Günther! Do you have a fire extinguisher?

540
00:57:08,550 --> 00:57:12,130
Yeah, that's right. He stuck it on there. None of that's in the script.

541
00:57:12,130 --> 00:57:14,350
That's my soul.

542
00:57:14,810 --> 00:57:17,170
Here's another one.

543
00:57:26,460 --> 00:57:33,800
I always felt like the best scene in Spider-Man, or the best scenes, were him learning to use this, climb the wall,

544
00:57:33,800 --> 00:57:37,094
and use the web shooter- the learning curve.

545
00:57:37,094 --> 00:57:43,760
So instead of rushing through this stuff, I really wanted to have fun and explore it.

546
00:57:49,460 --> 00:57:55,780
And that was, I think, an improvised line.

547
00:57:56,000 --> 00:57:59,000
This set we called the "Night Clubbers, Part 1."

548
00:58:00,440 --> 00:58:06,900
He's playing a little soliare there. A little...

549
00:58:07,640 --> 00:58:11,940
like in Amadeus

550
00:58:11,940 --> 00:58:13,600
there's jealousy.

551
00:58:16,800 --> 00:58:21,040
That's public domain, so I saved another 50 grand for Marvel.

552
00:58:23,140 --> 00:58:27,640
Ray's Pizza. Thought it was a nice touch. Those of you from New York...

553
00:58:27,640 --> 00:58:32,500
He's flying in on his G5. He's bringing pizza from Ray's Pizza.

554
00:59:18,080 --> 00:59:19,947
So there's a constant tug-of-war here.

555
00:59:19,947 --> 00:59:24,860
Because Marvel always wants it sort of straightforward, and we always want to do something different

556
00:59:24,860 --> 00:59:27,140
and interesting, and...

557
00:59:28,200 --> 00:59:34,960
We're afraid we'll confuse people if you learn up front enough about things. I think we struck a nice balance.

558
00:59:41,400 --> 00:59:45,160
Those sound effects, too, by the way, came out of when we were up at Skywalker Ranch doing it,

559
00:59:45,160 --> 00:59:47,980
so a lot of that stuff is...

560
00:59:50,560 --> 00:59:52,340
Ben Burtt...

561
00:59:52,340 --> 00:59:54,960
Those Ben Burtt sounds.

562
00:59:55,280 --> 01:00:03,560
So that's a feeling like WALL-E or R2-D2 or Star Wars. It's just coming from the same library of sounds.

563
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:15,000
What is so funny about being mean to inanimate objects?

564
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:20,097
And because we went in order, if I threw a joke around like that...

565
01:00:20,097 --> 01:00:23,400
That's how the whole runner came about, of the

566
01:00:23,400 --> 01:00:26,140
fire extinguisher hitting him.

567
01:00:34,660 --> 01:00:40,940
So he would make up a line like that, and then there would be an opportunity to pay it off later.

568
01:00:43,900 --> 01:00:46,480
The humor, the humor, the humor. Come on.

569
01:00:48,440 --> 01:00:52,840
And the script was pretty straight ahead. There wasn't a lot of humor in the script.

570
01:00:52,880 --> 01:01:00,300
There was some dialogue that was clever, like the stuff you do with Pepper, but the action stuff was very straight ahead.

571
01:01:13,420 --> 01:01:17,720
I was right before last time, and I felt like we'd done a good half-day at that point.

572
01:01:19,920 --> 01:01:24,300
So look at the Army of Darkness suiting up shots.

573
01:01:30,390 --> 01:01:38,190
So this HUD was another big thing. How do you show him inside the suit? Because this is the one suit where you

574
01:01:38,190 --> 01:01:45,330
can actually get inside. In Spider-Man, you've got to take the mask off. In Batman, you can't do that.

575
01:01:45,530 --> 01:01:50,310
This is just awesome right here. It's all ILM.

576
01:01:51,530 --> 01:01:55,930
So some of this is CGI. I think they ended up replacing most of it with CGI.

577
01:01:55,930 --> 01:02:04,070
We filmed a real suit, and then they did the collapse work. And that's Tom Morello playing guitar.

578
01:02:12,970 --> 01:02:17,570
So everything on this HUD, we know what it means.

579
01:02:17,570 --> 01:02:25,430
There's a whole thought process behind all these little widgets and calibrations.

580
01:02:54,750 --> 01:03:00,330
We have a couple very special guest appearances coming up here.

581
01:03:02,450 --> 01:03:03,270
Let's see.

582
01:03:03,270 --> 01:03:06,250
We've got the Favreau children.

583
01:03:06,250 --> 01:03:08,510
There we go.

584
01:03:34,670 --> 01:03:40,610
We really want to capture that feeling of when you look up. I'm kind of afraid of flying.

585
01:03:40,610 --> 01:03:45,090
And that feeling you get when you come into LAX and you're looking down.

586
01:03:52,270 --> 01:03:59,870
That sort of grid, the electrical grid. The way it twinkles. What it really feels like.

587
01:03:59,870 --> 01:04:02,630
You get a sense of vertigo.

588
01:04:06,090 --> 01:04:09,470
That ice still looks like shit to me.

589
01:04:11,970 --> 01:04:15,970
That was in the last step we were working on.

590
01:04:26,870 --> 01:04:31,770
It's so fun because you drive home from work and you come up with ideas.

591
01:04:32,310 --> 01:04:37,530
Wouldn't it be cool if there was a house on Point Dume? If I could fly, I would go past

592
01:04:37,530 --> 01:04:39,590
the ferris wheel.

593
01:04:51,910 --> 01:05:04,290
So if Robert hadn't improvised the line about don't spray me with that thing, then we never would have done that after.

594
01:05:04,290 --> 01:05:10,090
So it was a real partnership. And I'd say some of the best moments, I guess it happens in every movement, some

595
01:05:10,090 --> 01:05:16,550
of the best moments, certainly in this one, came from unexpected things happening. And really

596
01:05:16,550 --> 01:05:22,570
following the improviser's creed that I was brought up with of just saying "yes and."

597
01:05:27,320 --> 01:05:32,840
And this also led to something. It sure does. It figures into act 3, and was never

598
01:05:32,840 --> 01:05:36,020
part of the script. It wasn't part of the script. It was just a prop I had made

599
01:05:36,020 --> 01:05:42,020
that I thought would be a nice way for them to bond. Which was that she would take this thing

600
01:05:42,020 --> 01:05:50,720
that he said throw away and then she made a little romantic gesture with it.

601
01:05:51,020 --> 01:05:56,300
And then... Why didn't you ask him to twist the ring right there? Because it was already close enough in the

602
01:05:56,300 --> 01:05:58,140
foreground? Yeah.

603
01:05:58,660 --> 01:06:06,000
To lead people to believe we really know what we're doing... down the road. I like that little...

604
01:06:06,040 --> 01:06:07,640
It's complicated.

605
01:06:08,560 --> 01:06:12,160
It's precise. Take to heart. Yes.

606
01:06:13,820 --> 01:06:16,160
And I turn over this shoulder.

607
01:06:16,160 --> 01:06:19,980
So this is another big argument.

608
01:06:20,100 --> 01:06:22,860
Marvel was like, why is he drinking the green shit?

609
01:06:24,060 --> 01:06:29,100
And I said, Robert, his whole character, he's got a whole thing he's doing. They said, well, why?

610
01:06:29,100 --> 01:06:31,180
I said, I don't know. I'll ask him.

611
01:06:31,180 --> 01:06:38,220
He felt very strongly about it. Because he was healing his body using these superfoods.

612
01:06:38,220 --> 01:06:41,020
Right? Wasn't that basically it? Yes.

613
01:06:41,920 --> 01:06:49,060
By the way, there's nothing quite as fun as having an Arc Reactor surgically glued to your sternum every morning.

614
01:07:18,510 --> 01:07:25,590
Again, so great to get the idea from the car that he worked on with his dad.

615
01:07:25,590 --> 01:07:28,010
Which is actually Jon's car.

616
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:44,000
Audi power!

617
01:07:47,710 --> 01:07:54,330
Look at that. I could always work on commercials if this doesn't work out.

618
01:07:56,570 --> 01:08:03,850
This is... This is the best use of Stan Lee in a movie ever.

619
01:08:03,870 --> 01:08:05,490
Coming up.

620
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:12,000
There you go.

621
01:08:25,950 --> 01:08:28,290
Jeff's first night.

622
01:08:29,390 --> 01:08:33,590
And Gwyneth's first night. In the movie.

623
01:08:34,170 --> 01:08:38,029
She was... Gwyneth was like, I really work best

624
01:08:38,310 --> 01:08:41,510
before like... eight or nine.

625
01:08:41,510 --> 01:08:46,109
I said cool. It's that kids' idea. Yeah, I get it.

626
01:08:46,109 --> 01:08:51,330
Sure enough, it was like three in the morning when she had her first shot.

627
01:08:51,430 --> 01:08:57,150
I added that "Gift of the Stark Foundation" [on the wall]. It adds a little touch there.

628
01:09:18,250 --> 01:09:25,149
So she's supposed to look the most ravishing in the whole movie as she ever does.

629
01:09:25,149 --> 01:09:30,330
She doesn't dye her hair. She has beautiful blonde hair. So this is all wigs.

630
01:09:30,330 --> 01:09:32,350
This red hair.

631
01:09:33,310 --> 01:09:34,810
And...

632
01:09:35,750 --> 01:09:39,110
I don't know that we really got there with this wig.

633
01:09:40,990 --> 01:09:44,390
But I do like this scene a lot.

634
01:09:47,069 --> 01:09:54,950
I like writing dialogue for this kind of stuff. They did a good job improvising around it.

635
01:09:58,170 --> 01:10:03,910
But she said that. Gwyneth said that, when we were rehearsing. See what I do is I write down

636
01:10:03,910 --> 01:10:06,406
everything that people say what they rehearse.

637
01:10:06,406 --> 01:10:10,530
And she should say something. She should say something like, I'm not wearing

638
01:10:10,530 --> 01:10:15,690
deodorant. And I'll just write everything down. And it would be in the script.

639
01:10:15,690 --> 01:10:20,970
And I knew she'd do a good job with the lines because she said them already.

640
01:10:21,490 --> 01:10:27,150
I usually like to make the character fit the actor more than the actor fit the character.

641
01:10:27,150 --> 01:10:31,350
And I knew Gwyneth, and this is actually not far from what she... She's more like this than in most of

642
01:10:31,350 --> 01:10:37,250
the roles that I've seen her in. And so just to find something that you can really knock out of park.

643
01:10:37,250 --> 01:10:41,730
And really show what's charming and interesting and quirky about her.

644
01:10:43,710 --> 01:10:47,870
I don't think there was anything written here. This is just me feeding you guys lines until it takes, right?

645
01:10:47,870 --> 01:10:50,070
Say this, say this.

646
01:10:55,890 --> 01:10:57,650
Two cameras.

647
01:11:08,470 --> 01:11:13,710
This is one of those scenes where everybody from the studio is like looking at you like you're crazy because it's 4 in the

648
01:11:13,710 --> 01:11:21,190
morning and you're doing ten takes and you're running in and you're telling them to say something completely different from the last time.

649
01:11:23,240 --> 01:11:26,137
We actually, they did really kiss.

650
01:11:26,137 --> 01:11:33,720
And through playing film backwards here and stopping things and using another focus shot...

651
01:11:33,720 --> 01:11:38,500
we were able to piece together an almost-kiss. Look at her right now.

652
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:48,200
Cut that out, why is that in there? What does it mean?

653
01:11:48,200 --> 01:11:54,260
You have to follow this. These are Jon's jokes that are kind of so quick and subtle that happen right now

654
01:11:54,260 --> 01:11:57,460
that they almost need to be reiterated.

655
01:12:26,220 --> 01:12:31,700
Leslie Bibb. She was a real, she was a treat.

656
01:12:32,800 --> 01:12:38,360
Starring in Midnight Meat Train [2008]. I don't know whose thumbs they are, but it looks like a murderer.

657
01:13:01,540 --> 01:13:06,740
Good looping, by the way, Robert. Look at that. Unusable sound here.

658
01:13:06,740 --> 01:13:11,680
He's very good at that. I'll tell him. Picture time.

659
01:13:12,460 --> 01:13:16,800
That's what Robert would say to me in every country. Picture time.

660
01:13:22,510 --> 01:13:26,070
Should we tell him here? Should we not tell him here? Should we not?

661
01:13:26,070 --> 01:13:31,750
I don't know. You're so adamant about it. When you watch the movie, it doesn't matter.

662
01:13:31,750 --> 01:13:38,110
But we fight back and forth over those things for months on end. You can't tell him he filed the injunction

663
01:13:38,110 --> 01:13:42,030
yet because of the... Nobody. Nobody cares.

664
01:13:42,030 --> 01:13:48,090
Speaking of something else Jon said: I want you to just shut up, stare at the screen, be a badass,

665
01:13:48,090 --> 01:13:52,150
and tweak your arm until I tell you to stand up. I was like, alright, dude.

666
01:13:52,150 --> 01:13:56,710
Whatever. Just tell me 10 minutes before we shoot, I'm gonna do a set.

667
01:14:07,530 --> 01:14:13,970
Now that was actually the real scene that we shot for the next action sequence that was shot by the second unit.

668
01:14:13,970 --> 01:14:20,550
Not this part. That little steel mill back there. And it was with the real suit.

669
01:14:20,550 --> 01:14:25,050
And it looked like an episode of Power Rangers. So we went back and used a CG

670
01:14:25,050 --> 01:14:31,670
suit and did a reshoot with the thing with the... the CG suit.

671
01:15:04,380 --> 01:15:08,120
So this wasn't originally in... And that's not Robert.

672
01:15:10,180 --> 01:15:12,320
But ILM... Whoever that guy is...

673
01:15:14,920 --> 01:15:20,400
But this is really awesome stuff that ILM did. It's all CG.

674
01:15:22,400 --> 01:15:32,240
When we cut money from the budget to get our green light, all the stuff where he was suiting up we

675
01:15:32,240 --> 01:15:39,360
cut out of the movie. Because we just cut from him getting ready to go to him in the suit, flying.

676
01:15:39,740 --> 01:15:44,120
Because it didn't affect the story. Then Transformers came out and made all this money.

677
01:15:44,120 --> 01:15:49,140
I said, guys, are you crazy? People are... We're gonna make $300 million just because

678
01:15:49,140 --> 01:15:54,060
people watched trucks turn into suits.

679
01:15:54,060 --> 01:15:56,820
We cut out everything in the movie...

680
01:15:59,800 --> 01:16:01,600
Sound barrier.

681
01:16:17,340 --> 01:16:27,220
So they gave us a couple million bucks more but we had no shootout sequences in the final moments of the film.

682
01:16:30,360 --> 01:16:32,760
This is all reshoots.

683
01:16:37,920 --> 01:16:41,340
So here's the trick with a superhero movie.

684
01:16:41,740 --> 01:16:46,720
You gotta make it so that everybody could root for the guy.

685
01:16:47,660 --> 01:16:56,160
If you just had Iron Man flying into some place killing a bunch of terrorists with low-tech weapons, and being a high-tech American hero,

686
01:16:56,160 --> 01:16:59,300
in every part of the world-

687
01:17:01,060 --> 01:17:03,298
it's tough to get behind that

688
01:17:03,298 --> 01:17:09,640
the same way you get behind Spider-Man saving a woman getting mugged in Central Park.

689
01:17:09,640 --> 01:17:16,460
So we have this little mini-scene that's interesting. That little boy is Faran's son.

690
01:17:16,460 --> 01:17:21,760
The guy who plays the other bad guy by the way. That's our little boy.

691
01:17:21,760 --> 01:17:23,300
This guy.

692
01:17:24,560 --> 01:17:30,780
So it looks like he's about to see his dad's reveal. I love this guy.

693
01:17:49,650 --> 01:17:55,170
I love gunfighter stuff. A little Robocop here.

694
01:18:05,170 --> 01:18:09,570
That's a stuntman from the valley.

695
01:18:09,930 --> 01:18:12,730
He's an Italian guy.

696
01:18:17,090 --> 01:18:21,070
So... this is also from Robocop, right?

697
01:18:21,070 --> 01:18:23,890
Did I steal that from Robocop?

698
01:18:34,530 --> 01:18:40,130
It's nice to know that the people you just saved have stomped somebody to death.

699
01:18:44,750 --> 01:18:47,910
This is CG. CGI right here. All of this.

700
01:18:47,910 --> 01:18:49,510
It's pretty amazing.

701
01:18:49,510 --> 01:18:51,110
Looks real.

702
01:18:51,110 --> 01:18:55,450
This is from the original test that The Orphanage [VFX studio] did for us.

703
01:18:56,710 --> 01:18:59,370
That was four figures in the movie.

704
01:19:06,710 --> 01:19:13,730
Now can somebody tell me why he doesn't use that against Jeff Bridges at the end? I don't know.

705
01:19:16,270 --> 01:19:19,870
He's saying the missile system is disabled.

706
01:19:20,270 --> 01:19:21,770
Whatever.

707
01:19:26,710 --> 01:19:33,350
We shot this scene twice and we rewrote it for a thousand years.

708
01:19:33,350 --> 01:19:37,390
I couldn't... We got it right though. I couldn't let go.

709
01:19:37,390 --> 01:19:39,660
But it sucked before and now it's good.

710
01:19:39,660 --> 01:19:43,910
So it actually came off. The re-shoots actually worked out really, really

711
01:19:43,910 --> 01:19:47,410
well for the first time in history.

712
01:19:47,770 --> 01:19:57,790
But the little interplay, the little interpersonal interplay between Robert and Terrence really made the scene keep the personality of the rest of the film.

713
01:19:59,150 --> 01:20:08,290
And that was because Robert showed up for the re-shoots here and actually was off camera working with him and they improvised once again.

714
01:20:25,030 --> 01:20:28,850
That was a nice touch there.

715
01:21:09,970 --> 01:21:17,270
So this was one of the original stuff we used for Comic-Con.

716
01:21:17,270 --> 01:21:23,600
Many of these are actual... actual plates where we had real airplanes doing this

717
01:21:23,600 --> 01:21:28,670
so that the sky movement, even though we painted over all the planes, felt real.

718
01:21:28,670 --> 01:21:31,289
It didn't feel like a big CG environment.

719
01:21:31,289 --> 01:21:36,250
So these were all real plates with real lens flare and real scratches.

720
01:21:36,790 --> 01:21:39,670
And of course mixed in are some CG.

721
01:21:45,990 --> 01:21:53,170
The cell phone is also going to be the theme from the 60s part here.

722
01:21:54,990 --> 01:22:03,000
We looked at Battlestar Galactica a lot. We really liked the camera work from that. How imperfect it was.

723
01:22:03,100 --> 01:22:05,100
The long lens work.

724
01:22:59,120 --> 01:23:02,000
Courtesy of Empire Strikes Back.

725
01:23:08,500 --> 01:23:16,820
The A/V had audio video toasters- it looks like a television station if you really look at the equipment.

726
01:23:31,500 --> 01:23:35,940
So we have real skydivers and stuff.

727
01:23:36,400 --> 01:23:42,200
They didn't have a real chair strapped to them, but we did have real skydivers when we were taking the chair in.

728
01:23:42,200 --> 01:23:48,460
I tried to do as much practical as I could for the plates. I was very, very reticent about it having

729
01:23:48,460 --> 01:23:51,040
too much of a CG look.

730
01:23:51,380 --> 01:23:58,420
We mix it up enough that I think that we really pulled it off where it's not glaring in your face, that something's fake.

731
01:24:43,287 --> 01:24:49,420
So Robert had improvised a line about the training exercise, and then I said, Oh, let's

732
01:24:49,420 --> 01:24:55,720
shoot a press conference where he says the training exercise. So, apparently, this is also part of the reshoot-

733
01:24:55,720 --> 01:24:58,820
apparently Obadiah Stane lives in a prop rental house.

734
01:25:01,400 --> 01:25:07,460
So if you don't have any money, just... See how he has his collar flipped up on his pajamas?

735
01:25:13,000 --> 01:25:16,660
Listen to this dialogue, it's so wrong.

736
01:25:19,500 --> 01:25:22,000
Another reshoot.

737
01:25:35,930 --> 01:25:40,770
I don't know who came up with that, if it was Robert or me, but it just happened.

738
01:25:42,310 --> 01:25:52,630
A laugh at the end of a scene or action sequence will save you the scrutiny that you would otherwise be subject to.

739
01:26:02,700 --> 01:26:09,980
So basically all the stuff that was supposed to be plot wise, significant stuff, never really landed that hard.

740
01:26:09,980 --> 01:26:15,140
So I just tried to make the movie as fun and funny as it could be.

741
01:26:16,900 --> 01:26:22,920
So there's just enough of this stuff to make you believe it's a movie, I guess.

742
01:26:27,820 --> 01:26:31,080
The parking lot at Buena Vista.

743
01:26:36,520 --> 01:26:42,620
I remember I wasn't working that day and I drove by and I go, wow, here's the big scene.

744
01:26:59,800 --> 01:27:07,000
Again, if you like the dialogue in any of these scenes, there's a four times as long version of every scene.

745
01:27:42,490 --> 01:27:49,230
So that's an effect, a CG effect that a company called LOMA did for us, those veins.

746
01:27:49,870 --> 01:27:55,170
And this effect with this cheap little prop and the cheap little lights in the ears, it was like...

747
01:27:55,170 --> 01:28:00,950
And the acting, how do you act when you're paralyzed? What did Jeff do when you said, how

748
01:28:00,950 --> 01:28:04,950
would you do it? Jeff said, how is he going to do the paralysis thing?

749
01:28:04,950 --> 01:28:11,310
I said, you're an Academy Award nominated actor, show me. And he flipped on the floor and shook

750
01:28:11,310 --> 01:28:17,730
around like an alligator. God bless him. I said, you're arguably one of the best

751
01:28:17,730 --> 01:28:24,170
actors of our generation. And that looked terrible. So if you can't do it, how can

752
01:28:24,170 --> 01:28:28,430
I ask these people to do it? And so it turned into them just being frozen.

753
01:28:28,430 --> 01:28:34,530
And then it looked like hell. We'll get to that later. So finally, we added that little visual effect

754
01:28:34,530 --> 01:28:40,390
that cost a couple grand that really sold the whole thing. It was amazing how sometimes it's that last

755
01:28:40,390 --> 01:28:46,090
little whipped cream that sells the whole thing. More importantly, this is where Jon Favreau saved my career.

756
01:28:46,090 --> 01:28:50,250
There was a cut of the scene where I flipped a table over while I'm getting emphatic.

757
01:28:50,250 --> 01:28:54,390
And on the playback, he told me I look not exactly like Prince.

758
01:28:55,970 --> 01:29:04,050
It wasn't even a table, it was a dentist tray with instruments on it. There it is.

759
01:29:04,330 --> 01:29:08,490
Next to the iron lung, or whatever else was in the prop house.

760
01:29:08,490 --> 01:29:12,321
You don't understand, it looks so like decisive.

761
01:29:12,321 --> 01:29:17,430
This is literally stuff that was used for like, you know, 1950s

762
01:29:17,930 --> 01:29:21,000
episodes of The Hulk or something.

763
01:29:44,000 --> 01:29:50,000
This is one of those scenes where we were up all night with people on set writing, wasn't it?

764
01:29:52,700 --> 01:29:56,700
I can't believe we're doing another one of these.

765
01:30:07,790 --> 01:30:14,170
They're good actors because... I don't know what's going on.

766
01:30:14,170 --> 01:30:17,950
There's nothing except the next mission!

767
01:30:19,770 --> 01:30:22,550
I mean, who do you sell that garbage to?

768
01:30:24,110 --> 01:30:31,130
But you gotta have it. If you don't have it though, the movie doesn't work.

769
01:30:31,130 --> 01:30:36,000
This is some nice sets, that [J. Michael] Riva built for us.

770
01:30:42,800 --> 01:30:48,320
And I'm saying, wait a minute. What is this, War Games? She's going to go into this thing.

771
01:30:48,320 --> 01:30:54,600
And she's going to do this with the fob. And he's going to come in and go... We're going to get slammed [by critics]!

772
01:30:54,600 --> 01:30:58,280
They're going to kill us. He [Jon] is like it's gonna be fine-

773
01:30:58,280 --> 01:31:02,080
Just because you're not in the scene doesn't mean it won't turn out.

774
01:31:12,380 --> 01:31:20,840
So we tried to create a whole interface, desktop for Stark, like he had his own thing. I mean, just hours of meetings.

775
01:31:21,580 --> 01:31:25,100
You really have to be obsessive to be a director.

776
01:31:25,380 --> 01:31:30,180
Because you spend 90% of your time picking fly shit out of pepper.

777
01:31:32,020 --> 01:31:38,020
They're like, what colors? How many folders should there be?

778
01:31:40,020 --> 01:31:43,960
They ask you and you have to tell them because you're the director.

779
01:31:56,160 --> 01:31:59,320
See, how it works? You just type in "translate."

780
01:32:00,540 --> 01:32:03,880
It's the same actor who reads the line.

781
01:32:17,320 --> 01:32:20,360
Oh, you found my Translite.

782
01:32:20,900 --> 01:32:24,580
I hate Translites. This one was actually pretty good.

783
01:32:30,020 --> 01:32:31,900
Thank you.

784
01:32:32,460 --> 01:32:34,320
Thank you.

785
01:32:35,360 --> 01:32:37,900
Somebody enjoyed that.

786
01:32:40,000 --> 01:32:44,000
I always enjoy that.

787
01:32:45,380 --> 01:32:54,560
They're in Tony's office and... there we go, cover it up with the Financial Times. He says, I like the puzzle.

788
01:32:55,040 --> 01:32:57,620
The Financial Times doesn't have a puzzle.

789
01:33:23,500 --> 01:33:26,010
For those of you who direct movies:

790
01:33:28,490 --> 01:33:35,210
You're in a lot of meetings and people talk about how much box office people make or who's the cost or this or that

791
01:33:35,210 --> 01:33:41,370
or who's hot. Always, always go with the best actor.

792
01:33:42,450 --> 01:33:46,250
Because... it will save your ass.

793
01:33:46,670 --> 01:33:51,950
But you kind of know what you're doing and you're kind of telling them what the scene's about and you kind of think you

794
01:33:51,950 --> 01:33:53,483
know what's happening.

795
01:33:53,483 --> 01:34:00,310
There's something that happens when good actors get together and they bring an authenticity to the

796
01:34:00,310 --> 01:34:02,810
subtext of the scene.

797
01:34:03,130 --> 01:34:08,830
That... it's a little bit of a shell game. And they...

798
01:34:09,890 --> 01:34:10,589
they just...

799
01:34:10,589 --> 01:34:16,410
bring significance to things that don't have any significance and bring gravity to things that don't

800
01:34:16,410 --> 01:34:19,630
justify it. And...

801
01:34:20,090 --> 01:34:28,500
it just classes everything up a lot. And we still have the same problems with this film that we had before...

802
01:34:28,500 --> 01:34:36,000
Why did you make her look at the fob in her hand even though we already see that she's got it?

803
01:34:37,370 --> 01:34:40,770
Then this was... When do we cut to this? I'm not standing for this stuff next time,

804
01:34:40,770 --> 01:34:42,470
I'll tell you that much.

805
01:34:42,810 --> 01:34:45,930
All the freedom in the world won't stand.

806
01:34:46,770 --> 01:34:51,910
It's actually funny. I like this with Clark [Gregg]. This feels...

807
01:34:59,290 --> 01:35:07,050
[Comparing hero archetypes] Eliot Ness from Untouchables... the accountant [Oscar Wallace]...

808
01:35:07,050 --> 01:35:16,310
Thanks, David [Hayter, writer]. Peter Billingsley here [Ralphie, A Christmas Story].

809
01:35:16,690 --> 01:35:20,590
Did you just pay for one day's work?

810
01:35:25,830 --> 01:35:28,590
Now I kind of know why I didn't have to do a commentary.

811
01:35:28,590 --> 01:35:32,670
Because we didn't really have much to say, do we? About this.

812
01:35:44,530 --> 01:35:46,510
Damn straight you're not.

813
01:35:49,990 --> 01:35:55,250
All right. This was the biggest trust exercise of my life.

814
01:35:55,890 --> 01:35:59,710
Because remember he was going to bring a box of pizza from Chicago? Yeah, yeah.

815
01:35:59,710 --> 01:36:05,450
I said I should have a gun under the table, and instead he said, no, just sit there frozen.

816
01:36:05,450 --> 01:36:09,410
While Jeff reads 39 pages of commentary.

817
01:36:10,370 --> 01:36:14,450
But those veins [VFX] helped. The veins did everything.

818
01:36:15,630 --> 01:36:20,350
And then the other thing that he pulls out the heart thing with... It's good.

819
01:36:20,350 --> 01:36:25,730
It's like a little machined aluminum prop that we added claws to in post-production.

820
01:36:25,730 --> 01:36:31,430
Just notice the great Jeff Bridges technique of taking his time.

821
01:36:32,270 --> 01:36:36,150
Sometimes about 12 seconds between each word.

822
01:36:42,530 --> 01:36:43,870
Look at that.

823
01:36:43,870 --> 01:36:46,000
That's pretty cool.

824
01:37:04,300 --> 01:37:08,770
See, in independent films, you don't have all this stuff to save you.

825
01:37:08,770 --> 01:37:13,620
All the little funny special effects and things.

826
01:37:29,120 --> 01:37:33,340
I like how Matty lit it with the light from that and it glints in his eyes.

827
01:37:33,340 --> 01:37:36,500
I like that line about the atomic bomb.

828
01:37:40,200 --> 01:37:43,660
We'll be here for hours, too.

829
01:38:57,500 --> 01:39:04,000
See there's going to be a SHIELD logo right there... there ya go. We snuck that in.

830
01:39:04,000 --> 01:39:07,660
We added that in post-production.

831
01:39:07,660 --> 01:39:11,100
And of course, another Audi.

832
01:39:11,780 --> 01:39:16,060
Because after all, how would they get around if not for Audis?

833
01:39:20,060 --> 01:39:24,980
This one's like hollowed out. And here, this is another discovery.

834
01:39:27,440 --> 01:39:31,760
So of course that's since we shot in order.

835
01:39:32,240 --> 01:39:35,160
There's a Stark 5, as opposed to a Mach 5.

836
01:39:38,100 --> 01:39:42,700
So as we were writing, as we were going along, we said, where's he going to get the heart if he gets the heart

837
01:39:42,700 --> 01:39:46,520
to the suit? And it was like, of course, the one that Pepper gave him.

838
01:39:53,420 --> 01:40:01,880
I always like the notion of people using things from display cases. You know, like, oh yeah, we figured out

839
01:40:01,880 --> 01:40:04,040
how he gets it.

840
01:40:04,700 --> 01:40:06,000
His little friend.

841
01:40:09,240 --> 01:40:15,178
Now he was actually, he actually starred in the commercial about the assembly line robot.

842
01:40:15,178 --> 01:40:17,380
Remember that for the Super Bowl [2007]?

843
01:40:17,380 --> 01:40:21,159
There's an assembly line robot that gets fired and wants to kill itself.

844
01:40:21,159 --> 01:40:23,000
Stan Winston built that, and they said,

845
01:40:23,000 --> 01:40:27,010
we'll have it for the background, and the puppeteers were having fun with it.

846
01:40:27,010 --> 01:40:30,740
And I told Robert, don't worry, we're going to have high-tech stuff in the shop,

847
01:40:30,740 --> 01:40:33,724
because you're Tony Stark, and it showed up, and it was these things.

848
01:40:33,724 --> 01:40:35,540
And that's why he ridiculed them the whole

849
01:40:35,540 --> 01:40:39,927
movie, because he said, this is not what Tony Stark would have.

850
01:40:39,927 --> 01:40:43,200
No, they were the dumbest robots ever invented.

851
01:41:14,250 --> 01:41:20,710
Where's Pepper? That was the one line that he refused to say in the whole movie.

852
01:41:20,710 --> 01:41:29,590
It's Tony, where's Pepper? Kent Brody: we must find Obadiah. I was like, I won't do it.

853
01:41:29,970 --> 01:41:31,374
I refused to say, where's Pepper?

854
01:41:31,374 --> 01:41:35,330
Jeremy Latcham, the co-producer, would always come up, because he worked for Marvel,

855
01:41:35,330 --> 01:41:38,690
and he'd be like, what we really need you to say in this scene is, where's Pepper?

856
01:41:39,370 --> 01:41:42,290
And he would just ride him.

857
01:41:43,250 --> 01:41:47,930
Here, remember, sector 16, down here is section 16.

858
01:41:48,330 --> 01:41:50,750
It doesn't seem to matter.

859
01:41:51,290 --> 01:41:58,630
There it is, section 16. Here's my little cinematic thing there. There's a pull-back.

860
01:41:58,630 --> 01:42:01,000
I like this- more my speed.

861
01:42:09,350 --> 01:42:12,090
So that was like the joke that they made.

862
01:42:12,090 --> 01:42:14,930
Look how he just folds his arms.

863
01:42:15,930 --> 01:42:20,990
But that's the type of stuff they kept trying to make me cut out. And I'd slip a little bit back in.

864
01:42:20,990 --> 01:42:27,310
They'd make me cut it out. It makes you weak and unlikable. No, it makes her human and cool.

865
01:42:34,790 --> 01:42:39,290
You're in the real suit for this. This is Robert in the real suit.

866
01:42:42,330 --> 01:42:44,730
Keep the skies clear.

867
01:43:01,070 --> 01:43:07,310
So that wasn't in the script either, but we just saw it hanging there. And we said, wouldn't it be funny if...

868
01:43:07,310 --> 01:43:10,270
Let's do the entire sequel on that moment.

869
01:43:11,910 --> 01:43:15,950
We're like, should he be trying to put the helmet on? It can't fit.

870
01:43:17,070 --> 01:43:20,070
So we just had the "next time, baby."

871
01:43:22,880 --> 01:43:28,160
What did they say this is? The Ridley Scott homage? Alien kind of.

872
01:43:28,160 --> 01:43:30,321
Yeah, that was a shot from Alien.

873
01:43:30,321 --> 01:43:34,700
Most of the shots I steal I remember. I remember consciously stealing them.

874
01:43:34,700 --> 01:43:46,780
This one was subconscious. But I think this is a shot from Alien coming up, though not done as well.

875
01:43:47,320 --> 01:43:51,540
So now you need that shot to show that he didn't die.

876
01:43:52,080 --> 01:43:54,820
That was a big argument. Oh, geez.

877
01:43:56,400 --> 01:43:59,120
Here's the shot of him jumping over the rail.

878
01:43:59,720 --> 01:44:00,920
Yes.

879
01:44:01,180 --> 01:44:04,580
And the world is safe once again.

880
01:44:04,940 --> 01:44:06,440
This one.

881
01:44:06,700 --> 01:44:09,280
The chain spread.

882
01:44:12,880 --> 01:44:14,640
Heavily storyboarded.

883
01:44:29,520 --> 01:44:34,580
That was Gwen running on a broken leg. She didn't know she had a broken leg.

884
01:44:34,960 --> 01:44:38,960
She said my leg's hurting a little bit.

885
01:44:56,840 --> 01:45:03,000
Why the hell is there a tank with like a label on it? Like they sell tanks.

886
01:45:06,840 --> 01:45:09,720
With a mileage sticker on it.

887
01:45:10,720 --> 01:45:12,520
This one has airbags.

888
01:45:15,520 --> 01:45:17,520
That's pretty cool.

889
01:45:28,460 --> 01:45:34,900
Roxxon, for you Marvel fans, there's a couple Roxxon logos

890
01:45:34,900 --> 01:45:37,340
on the trucks.

891
01:45:58,740 --> 01:46:07,280
This dialogue when superheroes are fighting is the hardest thing you've ever heard. Up to the looping stage.

892
01:46:09,440 --> 01:46:13,000
It's so hard to make it sound bad.

893
01:46:15,380 --> 01:46:17,800
I like that.

894
01:46:23,920 --> 01:46:26,580
There's a Roxxon logo.

895
01:46:32,520 --> 01:46:39,340
So originally, he was supposed to be... Rhodey was going to come up in the R8 and ram into him and knock

896
01:46:39,340 --> 01:46:44,960
him into the hydrogen bus, and the bus was going to blow up. I thought that was funny.

897
01:46:46,120 --> 01:46:50,460
He was going to just fall gingerly into the hydrogen bus and it was going to blow up

898
01:46:50,460 --> 01:46:57,660
like the Hindenburg. And that's where that plate was from. So, the car came up and would hit

899
01:46:57,660 --> 01:47:04,860
him, bang him into it, and instead we used that explosion for this. But that was what was going to happen

900
01:47:04,860 --> 01:47:08,860
when he fell gingerly into the hydrogen bus.

901
01:47:09,200 --> 01:47:13,340
So, Audi was not very happy when they heard what we did.

902
01:47:18,000 --> 01:47:25,720
This is all new. So, the last action sequence wasn't seen to have enough action when we cut that out.

903
01:47:25,980 --> 01:47:34,140
And so, it was like three weeks left to create a new action sequence in the end.

904
01:47:34,140 --> 01:47:43,220
And so, all of this stuff with the flying of all re-purposed plates and CGI that was done by ILM.

905
01:47:45,480 --> 01:47:51,060
And then we shot this in the reshoot. It was more than three weeks, but it was not enough time.

906
01:47:52,160 --> 01:47:56,820
So, we used a training exercise bit again, to tie it together.

907
01:48:14,040 --> 01:48:21,000
And we tried to call back to the ice thing, but there was something in the setup that wasn't as strong as it

908
01:48:21,000 --> 01:48:23,680
should have been.

909
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:55,000
We're gonna have a hell of an Act 3 next time, I promise.

910
01:49:11,550 --> 01:49:13,690
Cut.

911
01:49:13,690 --> 01:49:17,180
I'm still standing here.

912
01:50:38,090 --> 01:50:40,430
That's the one.

913
01:50:51,410 --> 01:50:55,150
That was a Robert mask on a stunt double.

914
01:50:55,630 --> 01:50:59,930
A rubber Robert mask...

915
01:51:00,630 --> 01:51:03,210
That's pretty cool.

916
01:51:04,490 --> 01:51:07,980
All the little pieces moving around in there.

917
01:51:07,980 --> 01:51:13,410
It was actually like a little, what we call the teapot, which was a...

918
01:51:14,710 --> 01:51:17,530
It was a...

919
01:51:18,570 --> 01:51:24,170
It was a piece that was on a dolly that they would push and he could move back and forth to emulate the movement

920
01:51:24,170 --> 01:51:28,210
of the suit and we were going to build the suit around him, which we did.

921
01:51:29,130 --> 01:51:36,390
We were going to start to integrate him more into the actual movement of the suit, and he felt pasted on.

922
01:51:36,390 --> 01:51:41,690
When we looked at the stuff of Doc Ock, it was like he was floating in front of a green screen and we

923
01:51:41,690 --> 01:51:47,990
wanted to have more parallax and more perspective shift and so we designed a whole rig for him.

924
01:51:47,990 --> 01:51:50,290
That's all miniatures.

925
01:51:50,290 --> 01:51:56,710
That whole inside the silo was miniature. I'm a big fan of miniatures- that special effects.

926
01:52:09,190 --> 01:52:14,000
This is a completely practical effect coming up.

927
01:52:15,330 --> 01:52:17,000
Right there.

928
01:52:17,390 --> 01:52:25,030
Real missile, real arms, real actor, real explosion. Everything else was doctored in some way.

929
01:52:26,830 --> 01:52:30,350
Why didn't Pepper die?? Well, there's the answer...

930
01:52:31,650 --> 01:52:34,130
Get it...?

931
01:52:39,000 --> 01:52:41,000
Weird Science!

932
01:52:46,870 --> 01:52:57,690
He was supposed to land, and there were more hanging there with dead suits for another five days of dialogue.

933
01:52:57,690 --> 01:53:07,730
And we left it out, after we paid for the CG. That explosion brought helicopters and the police force.

934
01:53:08,210 --> 01:53:13,570
He said we were going to have an explosion at 10, but we thought something went wrong.

935
01:53:13,570 --> 01:53:20,410
We fried $180,000 worth of lights, our second unit did. We went on an insurance claim.

936
01:53:29,550 --> 01:53:36,570
Now, once again, I like the dialogue. Gotta have good actors. But that's just me.

937
01:53:47,290 --> 01:53:51,500
So we got in a lot of trouble for that [newspaper] picture up there

938
01:53:51,500 --> 01:53:56,000
because when we were filming on the highway, some people from a website

939
01:53:56,000 --> 01:54:03,790
snuck in and filmed us filming, and put that on their website. Those were the first pictures that came out.

940
01:54:03,790 --> 01:54:10,270
I thought it would be really fun to put the picture from the picture they took from us as the picture in the movie.

941
01:54:10,270 --> 01:54:14,430
It was really cool, and then they sued Marvel for $5 million.

942
01:54:15,130 --> 01:54:21,330
So I don't know where it settled, but that's what you get for trying to be cool.

943
01:54:33,490 --> 01:54:39,230
That's the cover story from the comic books, by the way. Iron Man was his bodyguard.

944
01:54:41,470 --> 01:54:46,390
So we pay homage to it. This is how we work SHIELD in.

945
01:55:00,070 --> 01:55:03,150
I didn't think you guys would believe that.

946
01:55:10,227 --> 01:55:17,110
So this was two cameras completely improvised. We got three versions of this scene that I loved.

947
01:57:04,190 --> 01:57:07,770
Getting a lot of truth in Robert doing his thing.

948
01:57:08,270 --> 01:57:11,410
I'm going to look right in the pipe for this right here.

949
01:57:12,710 --> 01:57:14,810
I am Iron Man.

950
01:57:15,770 --> 01:57:17,270
So...

951
01:57:19,190 --> 01:57:23,810
But that seemed like a really good idea to tell everyone, I am Iron Man.

952
01:57:28,770 --> 01:57:30,270
Until...

953
01:57:31,270 --> 01:57:35,010
Until we set out to make the next one and we're like, wow, everybody knows he's Iron Man.

954
01:57:35,010 --> 01:57:39,930
I don't know what the heck he does. He can either wake up from a dream,

955
01:57:40,230 --> 01:57:41,275
or we gotta live with it.

956
01:57:41,275 --> 01:57:44,910
And it's actually cool because it makes it different from all the superhero movies now.

957
01:57:44,910 --> 01:57:52,310
I love, by the way, these low-tech, like, line vector graphics.

958
01:57:52,310 --> 01:57:57,000
Of course, Marvel was saying, hey, why don't we have... Oh, there's the Ten Rings thing.

959
01:57:57,000 --> 01:58:01,970
There's a little War Machine- a little teaser for the next movie.

960
01:58:01,970 --> 01:58:04,610
But I love the...

961
01:58:12,150 --> 01:58:18,150
I love the line vector, low-tech, shuddering,

962
01:58:18,410 --> 01:58:22,657
you know, bad-com looking credit sequence here.

963
01:58:22,657 --> 01:58:30,610
And of course, Marvel wanted 3D CGI, like Spider-Man...

964
01:58:30,610 --> 01:58:38,690
But I just... I just got this. And that's the SHIELD logo.

965
01:58:39,190 --> 01:58:44,850
So, ya know Jonny... We have a bonus scene. What's he talking?

966
01:58:44,850 --> 01:58:49,870
We got six minutes, guys. If you have to pee, go run out and come back.

967
01:58:49,870 --> 01:59:00,390
So, I had the Sam Jackson scene here. And then, up in ILM... not ILM, up in Skywalker...

968
01:59:01,110 --> 01:59:04,770
Edgar Wright, the director, came out.

969
01:59:04,770 --> 01:59:12,090
He was like the first person to see this in the Stag Theater at Skywalker.

970
01:59:12,090 --> 01:59:21,710
Skywalker, by the way, just to be able to mix a movie at Skywalker in the Kurosawa mixing stage was phenomenal.

971
01:59:21,710 --> 01:59:27,450
Because Lucas built, you know, basically a whole facility for him. And he rents it out to other people

972
01:59:27,450 --> 01:59:33,350
to make it a business. But it's like what you would do if you had all the money in the world,

973
01:59:33,350 --> 01:59:39,090
were a complete film geek, and wanted to collect every authentic film poster there was, and build everything

974
01:59:39,090 --> 01:59:46,130
as though Frank Lloyd Wright had built it, in the most beautiful part of the world you could buy real estate in- this part of

975
01:59:46,130 --> 01:59:48,850
Marin County, just thousands of acres.

976
01:59:48,850 --> 01:59:52,650
But anyway, Edgar Wright was up there visiting.

977
01:59:52,650 --> 01:59:55,910
And I showed him this film. He says, I love it! I love it!

978
01:59:55,910 --> 01:59:58,790
I love it! It's great! Really?

979
01:59:58,790 --> 02:00:04,650
Oh, it's great! He says, the one thing you gotta do, he says, you can't have that bonus scene

980
02:00:04,650 --> 02:00:05,370
right there.

981
02:00:05,370 --> 02:00:09,710
Put it at the end of the credits. I said, really? He says, yeah.

982
02:00:09,710 --> 02:00:13,670
Don't just give it to them. Put it all the way at the end. Let people miss it.

983
02:00:13,670 --> 02:00:17,010
I said, really? He says, yes.

984
02:00:17,010 --> 02:00:22,030
So, of course, then Marvel, when they saw that I switched it to the end, was like, why the hell did you do that?

985
02:00:22,030 --> 02:00:27,870
And then the word got out that there was a scene at the end. And then people came back to see the

986
02:00:27,870 --> 02:00:29,995
movie just to see the 30 second scene.

987
02:00:29,995 --> 02:00:34,470
And I think the fact that they have such a long credit sequence here that people

988
02:00:34,470 --> 02:00:39,650
would sit through, it was responsible for $10 million at the box office.

989
02:00:40,050 --> 02:00:45,110
So then Jon says, so hey, listen, we're just going to shoot some of these things for like, you know, a little bomb shoot.

990
02:00:45,110 --> 02:00:50,570
They'll probably ask you to do one for the Hulk, whatever. So, you're just going to come into your

991
02:00:50,570 --> 02:00:56,410
house but someone's broke in. And I said, god damn it. After everything he's been through, wouldn't he have upped

992
02:00:56,410 --> 02:01:01,290
his security? So I'm thinking again, like I say, why can he just walk into his house and so you

993
02:01:01,290 --> 02:01:04,370
would be like, well, he's from SHIELD. And I said, god damn it.

994
02:01:04,370 --> 02:01:06,630
It doesn't make any sense.

995
02:01:07,810 --> 02:01:11,110
He goes, well, Sam Jackson's gonna do it.

996
02:01:11,610 --> 02:01:14,010
So here he is.

997
02:01:14,010 --> 02:01:18,710
So Sam Jackson's the guy that in The Ultimate Avengers, for you guys who know comic books,

998
02:01:18,710 --> 02:01:22,210
they made look like Sam Jackson. I said, wouldn't that be cool for the fans?

999
02:01:22,210 --> 02:01:26,370
This is a Marvel movie. First time Marvel Studios is making its own movies.

1000
02:01:26,370 --> 02:01:30,230
Let's put as many little Easter eggs for the fans in there as we can. So we asked Sam, do you want to

1001
02:01:30,230 --> 02:01:33,570
do it? He said, sure. He came down, we kept it top secret.

1002
02:01:33,570 --> 02:01:41,470
We shot on a Saturday. Skeleton crew, nobody. It literally got out the next day.

1003
02:01:42,250 --> 02:01:47,510
So we struck all of our screening prints and even the premiere did not have the scene.

1004
02:01:47,510 --> 02:01:52,750
And everybody was up in arms because: You said it was in. It wasn't in. I knew it was in.

1005
02:01:52,750 --> 02:01:56,310
What did they do? What did they do? And then when it finally went to the

1006
02:01:56,310 --> 02:02:03,230
real theaters, we put the print back in with it on. And I think that the fans appreciated the

1007
02:02:03,230 --> 02:02:07,970
cat and mouse game we played. And so this went very well. And then for The Hulk, they said, hey,

1008
02:02:07,970 --> 02:02:10,810
why don't you do one for after the credits too?

1009
02:02:10,810 --> 02:02:14,590
And Robert says, should I do it? I said, why not? It's after the credits, whatever.

1010
02:02:15,350 --> 02:02:21,790
He goes and does it. And at the last minute, they decide instead of having it at the end of the credits, they ended

1011
02:02:21,790 --> 02:02:24,070
the movie with it.

1012
02:02:24,070 --> 02:02:26,284
It became the big ending of the movie.

1013
02:02:26,284 --> 02:02:30,830
Then Robert was going to walk in because... They were hoping I'd like to come and

1014
02:02:30,830 --> 02:02:33,850
see that they had made that change at the premiere.

1015
02:02:34,710 --> 02:02:42,170
And I was otherwise engaged. It was all part of the Marvel universe, and it was a marvelous universe.

1016
02:02:42,430 --> 02:02:46,850
But now if we do a sequel, we're trying to figure out what he's... In that movie, he goes up to the

1017
02:02:46,850 --> 02:02:50,050
bad guy and says, we're forming a team.

1018
02:02:50,750 --> 02:02:54,950
And clearly at the end of this movie, he's not forming a team of anything.

1019
02:02:55,270 --> 02:03:00,550
So where're we putting it in the timeline? How does he justify? Does he wake up from a dream?

1020
02:03:00,550 --> 02:03:04,470
That's always my part. He can wake up from a dream! Oh, okay.

1021
02:03:04,470 --> 02:03:07,250
It was a training exercise.

1022
02:03:09,470 --> 02:03:14,590
We pull back and it's a movie set in the movie. Like in Get Shorty.

1023
02:03:15,570 --> 02:03:20,850
See, we don't think about this stuff while we're doing it. That's what nobody knows.

1024
02:03:21,110 --> 02:03:24,270
You're just trying to bail water out of the boat.

1025
02:03:24,270 --> 02:03:29,250
You know? You get your fingers in all the holes in the dam.

1026
02:03:29,670 --> 02:03:32,813
And then you're so happy, and you're exhausted after you run the marathon.

1027
02:03:32,813 --> 02:03:34,470
And then you pick yourself up, and then

1028
02:03:34,470 --> 02:03:40,550
you realize you're only... You've got to do it again. By the way, for their code of loving

1029
02:03:40,550 --> 02:03:46,150
tolerance, I think we should give a hand to Joya Favreau and Susan Downey. Thank you.

1030
02:03:53,500 --> 02:03:58,000
Who stuck by our sides through thick and thin.

1031
02:03:58,310 --> 02:04:04,970
My wife, Joya, has left. She's not here anymore. Not the marriage, just the screening.

1032
02:04:04,970 --> 02:04:10,170
She's heard me talk enough. It got to the point where Susan would just come in and hand me the phone...

1033
02:04:10,170 --> 02:04:13,170
I'd go, who is this? Your girlfriend's on the phone.

1034
02:04:13,210 --> 02:04:16,000
I don't think that was me.

1035
02:04:17,030 --> 02:04:19,550
What about Captain America?

1036
02:04:20,010 --> 02:04:21,889
Oh yeah, I should have said that.

1037
02:04:21,889 --> 02:04:26,730
So there's a shield, a Captain America shield in the background of when he says, this

1038
02:04:26,730 --> 02:04:29,310
isn't the worst thing you caught me doing, that scene.

1039
02:04:29,310 --> 02:04:36,090
There's a shield in there with the Captain America logo on it, on his workbench. That was put in by a ILM guy.

1040
02:04:36,090 --> 02:04:42,570
And they showed it to us as a joke in the screening sessions. They were like, leave it in, man.

1041
02:04:42,570 --> 02:04:46,390
They love that kind of thing. Leave it in. And everybody picked it out.

1042
02:04:46,390 --> 02:04:52,350
Of course, it's like the person hanging themselves in Wizard of Oz now- it is really there?

1043
02:04:55,030 --> 02:04:58,950
So here comes scene that everybody waits 15 minutes to see.

1044
02:05:00,490 --> 02:05:04,330
As the run was coming up, more and more people would stay in the theater. In the beginning, it would just be like

1045
02:05:04,330 --> 02:05:07,570
10. By the end, it would be the whole house.

1046
02:05:08,110 --> 02:05:09,930
Here it is.

